    "body": "<!-- Thank you for your contribution! Please follow these guidelines to enhance your pull request. If anything is unclear, submit your PR and reach out to maintainers for assistance. Join our Slack community at https://slack.sglang.io to discuss further. -->\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\n### Memory Components\r\n\r\nWe decompose GPU memory usage into three components:\r\n\r\n- **Non-Torch Memory**  \r\n  GPU memory not managed by PyTorch’s CUDA caching allocator. For Piecewise CUDA Graph (PCG), this mainly corresponds to CUDA Graph metadata and runtime bookkeeping.\r\n\r\n- **Torch Dynamic Pool Memory**  \r\n  Memory allocated from PyTorch’s default CUDA caching allocator during eager execution.\r\n\r\n- **Torch Private Pool Memory**  \r\n  A dedicated allocator pool created for CUDA Graph capture, which contains all graph-captured tensor allocations.\r\n\r\nIn practice, PCG memory usage is primarily composed of **private pool memory and non-Torch memory**.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Memory Measurement\r\n\r\n- **Torch-managed memory (dynamic + private pools)**  \r\n  We use `torch.cuda.max_memory_allocated()` to measure the combined footprint of PyTorch-managed allocations, including both dynamic and CUDA Graph private pools.\r\n\r\n- **Non-Torch memory (approximate)**  \r\n  Non-Torch memory is not directly observable through PyTorch APIs. We estimate it using CUDA OOM diagnostics emitted by PyTorch.\r\n\r\n  Example:\r\n\r\n```\r\nIncluding non-PyTorch memory, this process has 139.32 GiB memory in use.\r\nOf the allocated memory 135.53 GiB is allocated by PyTorch,\r\nwith 572.00 MiB allocated in private pools (e.g., CUDA Graphs),\r\nand 265.53 MiB is reserved by PyTorch but unallocated.\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe estimate non-Torch memory as:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnon_torch_memory\r\n= process_memory_in_use\r\n- torch_allocated_memory\r\n- torch_reserved_but_unallocated_memory\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n### Experimental Results and Key Findings\r\n\r\nDetailed measurements, raw logs, and additional figures are available at:  \r\nhttps://www.notion.so/PCG-memory-usage-2e19a415e571800d9c53f872456e25e9\r\n\r\n#### Measurement Setup\r\n\r\n- **Qwen3-32B**, TP=2  \r\n- **LLaMA-70B**, TP=4  \r\n- **DeepSeek**, TP=8  \r\n- All experiments are conducted on **NVIDIA H200 GPUs**\r\n\r\nEach result reports extra memory usage relative to **PCG = 0**.\r\n\r\n#### Key Findings\r\n\r\n1. **Torch memory usage from PCG private pools is small and stable**  \r\n All piecewise CUDA graphs reuse the same private memory pool under the same CUDA Graph handler, so torch-managed memory growth from PCG is trivial and does not scale with PCG size.  \r\n When capturing chunked prefill execution, torch memory usage can even drop below the non-graph baseline, since temporary activation buffers are absorbed into the CUDA Graph private pool.\r\n\r\n2. **Non-Torch memory dominates PCG overhead**  \r\n Non-Torch memory is the main contributor to PCG overhead and corresponds to CUDA Graph metadata and runtime bookkeeping.  \r\n This overhead scales with the **number of CUDA Graph instances**, rather than the **maximum capture size** of a graph.\r\n\r\n<img\r\n  src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/99bbac58-f56d-4d1e-97c4-2d14a3163e3a\"\r\n  width=\"60%\"\r\n/>\r\n\r\n<img\r\n  src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/87b4dda5-b17a-40e5-91ae-069fa7b278ca\"\r\n  width=\"60%\"\r\n/>\r\n\r\n<img\r\n  src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4faf677d-19c7-4852-885a-e366a212fa48\"\r\n  width=\"60%\"\r\n/>\r\n\r\n### Policy Decisions\r\n\r\nBased on these results, we adopt the following PCG configuration policies:\r\n\r\n1. **Capture to chunk prefill size**  \r\n Capture CUDA Graphs at the chunk prefill size so all smaller prefill sizes can reuse the same graph, maximizing reuse and reducing torch memory usage.\r\n\r\n2. **Minimize the gap to large prefill sizes**  \r\n Reduce the gap between PCG capture sizes and large prefill sizes to limit the number of CUDA Graph instances, since non-Torch memory scales with graph count.\r\n\r\n3. **Conservative default for MLA models**  \r\n For MLA models, where PCG affects attention dispatch behavior, we set the default PCG max capture size to **2048**.\r\n\r\nThese policies ensure PCG achieves performance benefits while keeping both torch-managed and non-Torch memory overhead predictable and bounded.\r\n\r\n\r\n## Modifications\r\n\r\n## Accuracy Tests\r\n\r\n<!-- If this pull request affects model outputs (e.g., changes to the kernel or model forward code), provide accuracy test results. -->\r\n\r\n## Benchmarking and Profiling\r\n\r\nWith PR #15356 the pcg memory usage reduced from 5.32G to 1.45G for Llama 70B with TP=4.\r\nBy now most of the memory usage of PCG can be controlled within 1.5G which can be accepted by default solution.\r\n\r\n<!-- If this pull request impacts inference speed, provide benchmarking and profiling results. -->\r\n\r\n## Checklist\r\n\r\n- [ ] Format your code according to the [Format code with pre-commit](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#format-code-with-pre-commit).\r\n- [ ] Add unit tests according to the [Run and add unit tests](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#run-and-add-unit-tests).\r\n- [ ] Update documentation according to [Write documentations](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#write-documentations).\r\n- [ ] Provide accuracy and speed benchmark results according to [Test the accuracy](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#test-the-accuracy) and [Benchmark the speed](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#benchmark-the-speed).\r\n- [ ] Follow the SGLang code style [guidance](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#code-style-guidance).\r\n- [ ] Work with maintainers to merge your PR. See the [PR Merge Process](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/blob/main/.github/MAINTAINER.md#pull-request-merge-process)\r\n",
